orting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"049d6682-f78d-5c05-bdfb-1dbd5e91b017","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"58d7e6c5-f97f-507d-b627-87ab85bde479","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"574b8e96-33b9-5191-81dd-f415c704abf9","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"f3df8039-73c2-5c30-b7e8-2566977e32dc","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"d466274b-a2ab-58f1-badc-abfed7066e4f","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"aaed3513-3a59-5991-8410-2c4446539abd","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"74346084-c291-5a06-ac3d-a0ae85243940","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"59e978dc-e4bc-574d-a047-413f87ec6b3d","slug":"diagnosis","fullItemName":"Diagnosis"},"subChapters":[{"id":"e78e10a4-47c9-5a55-b14f-a34608b1474c","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-7cb","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field f86809bf-0bfe-4552-ac72-b55931fab9a7 --><h3>Basis for recommendation</h3><!-- end field f86809bf-0bfe-4552-ac72-b55931fab9a7 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 7cbd560f-b483-4748-a8e6-69a717c739ce --><!-- begin field 56f2aed7-df9f-43ad-9f84-6c092b43afd3 --><h4>Typical symptoms and signs of an acutely ischaemic limb</h4><ul><li>This information is based on expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/peripheral-arterial-disease/references/\">Brearley, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/peripheral-arterial-disease/references/\">Santistevan, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/peripheral-arterial-disease/references/\">Barraclough and Bradbury, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/peripheral-arterial-disease/references/\">Morley et al, 2018</a>].</li></ul><h4>Embolic and thrombotic acute limb ischaemia</h4><ul><li>This information is based on expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/peripheral-arterial-disease/references/\">Jaffery et al, 2011</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/peripheral-arterial-disease/references/\">Santistevan, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/peripheral-arterial-disease/references/\">McNally and Univers, 2018</a>]. <ul><li>Acute limb ischaemia is often thought to have a sudden onset. However, although this is typical for acute limb ischaemia of embolic origin, if the cause is thrombosis and underlying atherosclerosis, the onset can be more gradual, as collateral circulation can develop. This reduces the severity of ischaemia by maintaining some perfusion [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/peripheral-arterial-disease/references/\">Jaffery et al, 2011</a>].</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 56f2aed7-df9f-43ad-9f84-6c092b43afd3 --><!-- end item 7cbd560f-b483-4748-a8e6-69a717c739ce -->","subChapters":[]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}